act present in all social interaction. What changes over time and place are not, then, the absence or presence of affect and emotions, but rather the modes and calibrations of affective and emotional registers. In this manner, this essay works towards a theory of affect and the political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCulturexStudy and teaching. 0aEmotionsxSociological aspects. 0aEthnology. 0aPolitical sociology. 0aSocial sciences (General). 0aSocial sciences. 4aAffect. 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCultural Theory. 4aCulture. 4aEmotion. 4aEthnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aAffect.  aCultural Anthropology.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aEmotion.  aEthnology.1 aDiefenbach, Aletta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJohn, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLehmann, Hauke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLüthjohann, Matthias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOberkrome, Friederike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRoth, Hans, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aScheidecker, Gabriel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aThonhauser, Gerhard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aUral, Nur Yasemin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWahba, Dina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWalter-Jochum, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aZik, M. Ragip, 